Sure! Here's an example Matlab script that plots the graph of `` y = sin(x) `` using the `` plot `` function from the `` graph `` object:


```scss
% Load the required functions
load('sin_fun.m', 'sin_fun');
load('plot_fun.m', 'plot_fun');

% Define the range of x and y values
x = [0, 2*pi];
y = sin_fun(x);

% Create the plot object
plot_fun(x, y);
title('sin(x)');
xlabel('x');
ylabel('y');

```

This script first loads the `` sin_fun `` and `` plot_fun `` functions from two separate files, `` sin_fun.m `` and `` plot_fun.m ``, respectively. It then defines a range of values for `` x `` and `` y `` using the `` x `` and `` y `` variables, respectively. It creates a `` plot `` object by calling the `` plot_fun `` function, which, in turn, creates a scatter plot of `` x `` and `` y ``. The `` title ``, `` xlabel ``, and `` ylabel `` functions are used to add a title to the plot, labels to the x-axis and y-axis, and a y-axis label, respectively. Finally, the `` x `` and `` y `` values are plotted using the `` setxlim ``, `` setylim ``, `` setxticks ``, and `` setyticks `` functions, respectively, to adjust the range of values displayed on the x-axis and y-axis.
